{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"9c9a520f3e79bfe43359297300b85bfe4b24c7f3eb58e3c08c36d4d15eddc0e2","slug":"bayesian-vs-frequentist-reasoning","location":"/contents/Statistics/Bayesian vs Frequentist Reasoning.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Bayesian vs Frequentist Reasoning","content_includes_title":true,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Somnath Rakshit","given":"Somnath","family":"Rakshit"},"name":"Somnath Rakshit","email":"somnath52@gmail.com","id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0","corresponding":true}],"license":{"content":{"id":"MIT","url":"https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT","name":"MIT License","free":true,"osi":true}},"github":"https://github.com/somnathrakshit/mymlrecipes","numbering":{"title":{"offset":1}},"source_url":"https://github.com/somnathrakshit/mymlrecipes/blob/main/contents/Statistics/Bayesian vs Frequentist Reasoning.md","edit_url":"https://github.com/somnathrakshit/mymlrecipes/edit/main/contents/Statistics/Bayesian vs Frequentist Reasoning.md","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"Bayesian vs Frequentist Reasoning.md","url":"/build/Bayesian vs Frequent-4700f692ccaa508a9e3a3fb071afd05b.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":1,"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Bayesian vs Frequentist Reasoning","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"jM7RAyfEdQ"}],"identifier":"bayesian-vs-frequentist-reasoning","label":"Bayesian vs Frequentist Reasoning","html_id":"bayesian-vs-frequentist-reasoning","implicit":true,"key":"uHi1OGdYWL"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Bayesian statistics concerns itself with trying to represent your beliefs in a DeFinetti consistent manner, simply put - you want a logically rigorous way of describing your initial (prior) belief and the update in your belief as you observe new data (thus creating posterior belief).","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"XaSV9uImAB"}],"key":"bmyFbbNleG"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Frequentist statistics concerns itself with methods that have ‘long run’ guarantees.","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"key":"TS1UyVtqqh"}],"key":"mp609uYWuB"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"E.g. If a person shoots bullseye of the target 9 times, the frequentist approach predicts that 10th shot will also be bullseye. Whereas, as a human we are prone to making some error. The Bayesian approach will take this prior behavior into account. It will not predict 1 as the probability of hitting bullseye in 10th shot. It will take into account prior shots in similar situations and predict accordingly.","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"nWHCUiMFyB"}],"key":"XmMh8QO1QS"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In case of Web data, if a person has liked something 9 times, frequentist will predict that the person will like it 10th time as well. Where as, Bayesian approach knows that humans can get bored. Liking something 9 times does not guarantee that it will be liked 10th time as well.","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"IbNl2nBPjC"}],"key":"f32rBOqBZX"}],"key":"fSIU113QIS"}],"key":"MOan1lauqS"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Central Limit Theorem","url":"/central-limit-theorem","group":"Statistics"},"next":{"title":"Hypothesis Testing","url":"/hypothesis-testing","group":"Statistics"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3000"}